

High Modernism and Techn\'e9 in International Development

 This is my first serious attempt at examining high modernism in international development, and I\
am beginning to see how deeply its logic structures the sector. With its faith in rational planning,\
scientific expertise, and technical solutions, high modernism operates not only as a historical\
ideology but as an everyday mindset in development and humanitarian work. Across both\
academic literature and practice, I notice a strong reliance on the belief that complex
social problems can be addressed through better tools, systems, and measurement.\
One of its clearest expressions is the dominance of metrics. Development projects revolve\
around logframes, indicators, outputs, and measurable outcomes. Food security becomes the\
number of rations distributed; health becomes vaccination coverage rates; education becomes\
enrollment statistics. These tools are essential for accountability and coordination, especially at\
scale. Yet they also compress reality. What can be measured becomes what counts. Dignity,\
trust, cultural meaning, and informal coping systems rarely appear on a dashboard.\
With a background in cloud computing and systems architecture, I understand the appeal of\
technical order. Clean data pipelines, standardized processes, and traceable systems create\
clarity in chaotic environments. In humanitarian logistics, digital cash transfers and biometric\
identification can reduce fraud and increase efficiency. From a systems perspective, this is good\
design. But system coherence does not automatically produce social coherence.\
In Ghana, digital public service platforms illustrate this tension. Online portals for permits,\
identification, and health registration promise efficiency and transparency. On paper, they signal\
modernization. In practice, uneven internet access, digital literacy gaps, and bureaucratic\
discretion mean that many citizens still rely on intermediaries like cyber caf\'e9s, agents, and\
informal brokers to navigate the system. The technical solution exists, but social realities\
reshape its function.
The sector's enthusiasm for innovation further reflects this high modernist impulse. Hackathons,\
AI-powered targeting, blockchain-based aid distribution, and biometric verification are framed as\
transformative breakthroughs. Yet many pilots struggle because they overlook local trust\
networks, governance dynamics, or fears about data misuse. The tool becomes central, while\
the relational and political dimensions remain secondary.
